\section{Configuration}

The todo system stores its data in a configurable directory, defaulting
to [[~/.nytid/todos]]. We also allow configuring the maximum deadline
boost and work hours used when scheduling todos through
[[nytid schedule show]].

Why a separate directory from track data? Because todos have a different
lifecycle---they are created, prioritized, and completed, whereas track
entries are append-only historical records. Keeping them separate avoids
coupling the two storage formats.

<<configuration>>=
TODO_DIR_CONFIG = "todo.data_dir"
TODO_MAX_BOOST_CONFIG = "todo.max_boost"
TODO_WORK_START_CONFIG = "todo.work_start"
TODO_WORK_END_CONFIG = "todo.work_end"
TODO_WORK_DAYS_CONFIG = "todo.work_days"


def get_todo_dir() -> pathlib.Path:
    """Get the todo data directory path."""
    try:
        return pathlib.Path(
            config.get(TODO_DIR_CONFIG)
        )
    except KeyError:
        todo_dir = (
            pathlib.Path.home() / ".nytid" / "todos"
        )
        config.set(TODO_DIR_CONFIG, str(todo_dir))
        return todo_dir


def get_todo_file() -> pathlib.Path:
    """Get the path to the todos JSON file."""
    return get_todo_dir() / "todos.json"


DEFAULT_MAX_BOOST = 10.0


def get_max_boost() -> float:
    """Get the maximum deadline boost value."""
    return default(TODO_MAX_BOOST_CONFIG,
                   DEFAULT_MAX_BOOST, float)


DEFAULT_WORK_START = "08:00"


def get_work_start() -> str:
    """Get configured work day start time."""
    return default(TODO_WORK_START_CONFIG,
                   DEFAULT_WORK_START, str)


DEFAULT_WORK_END = "17:00"


def get_work_end() -> str:
    """Get configured work day end time."""
    return default(TODO_WORK_END_CONFIG,
                   DEFAULT_WORK_END, str)


DEFAULT_WORK_DAYS = "mon,tue,wed,thu,fri"


def get_work_days() -> list[str]:
    """Get configured work days as list.

    Handles both string (``"mon,tue,wed"``) and list
    (``["mon", "tue", "wed"]``) config formats.
    """
    days_val = default(TODO_WORK_DAYS_CONFIG,
                       DEFAULT_WORK_DAYS)
    if isinstance(days_val, list):
        days_val = ",".join(str(d) for d in days_val)
    return [d.strip().lower()
            for d in days_val.split(",")]
@

Worker-specific defaults need a different treatment from the global
settings above.  A teacher may want every task for [[dan-claude]] to run
[[opencode]] in one working directory with one captured environment,
without baking those choices into each todo item.

We therefore read worker defaults lazily from paths of the form
[[todo.worker.<worker>.<attribute>]].  Missing keys simply mean
no default.  These values are consulted only when a loaded todo leaves
the corresponding attribute unset, so explicit task metadata still wins.
For [[env]] the config value should be a JSON object so it maps cleanly
to a Python dictionary.

<<configuration>>=
WORKER_DEFAULT_ATTRIBUTES = (
    "command",
    "wd",
    "env",
)


def get_worker_default(worker, attribute):
    """Return the configured default for one worker attribute."""
    if not worker or not attribute:
        return None
    try:
        value = config.get(
            f"todo.worker.{worker}.{attribute}"
        )
    except KeyError:
        return None

    if attribute == "env":
        if not isinstance(value, dict):
            return None
        return {
            str(key): str(val)
            for key, val in value.items()
        }
    return value
@

\section{Data Model}

\subsection{The TodoItem Dataclass}

Each todo item carries an integer ID, a title, labels that connect to
the track system, an optional numeric priority, a
status, timestamps, an optional deadline, an estimated duration in
hours, a longer description, an optional parent ID for sub-items, and
an optional worker assignment.

To support work-session management (inspired by the UNIX [[at]]
command), each item can also capture the working directory and
environment at creation time, extended notes for the editor, and a
default command to run when starting the task. The [[wd]] and [[env]]
fields together let [[todo start]] restore the exact context in which
the task was conceived---solving the common problem of \enquote{where
was I working on this?} The [[command]] field defaults to [[$SHELL]]
but can be set to tools like [[claude]] or [[opencode]].

The optional [[github]] field links a todo to a GitHub issue or pull
request, enabling bidirectional synchronization. We store
the repository, item type, and number as a dictionary rather than
a URL string because the [[gh]] CLI needs these components
individually---parsing them back from a URL would be fragile and
redundant.

We use a dataclass rather than a plain class because the fields are
pure data with no complex invariants---unlike [[ActiveSession]] in
track, which manages mutable state with batch semantics.

Worker defaults are runtime policy, not persisted task data.  That
distinction matters when an item is loaded, viewed, and then saved again:
we want the in-memory object to behave as if missing [[command]],
[[wd]], or [[env]] were filled from the worker's config, but we do not
want an unrelated edit to write those defaults into [[todos.json]].

We solve that tension inside [[TodoItem]] itself.  Attribute reads for a
small set of worker-scoped fields consult [[get_worker_default()]] when
the stored value is [[None]], while [[to_dict()]] serializes the raw
stored values from [[__dict__]] rather than the runtime-resolved ones.
This keeps worker defaults memory-only even when a loaded todo passes
through a save cycle.  In other words, loading applies policy, while
saving preserves only what the item explicitly stored before the load.

<<data model>>=
@dataclass
class TodoItem:
    """A single todo item with priority and metadata.

    Items are stored in a JSON file and sorted by
    effective priority for display and scheduling.
    """

    id: int
    title: str
    labels: list[str] = field(default_factory=list)
    priority: float | None = 0.0
    status: str = "pending"
    created: str = ""
    deadline: str | None = None
    estimated: float | None = None
    description: str = ""
    parent_id: int | None = None
    who: str | None = None
    notes: str = ""
    wd: str | None = None
    env: dict[str, str] | None = None
    command: str | None = None
    github: dict[str, str] | None = None

    def to_dict(self) -> dict:
        """Convert explicit values to a JSON-serializable dict."""
        return {
            f.name: self.__dict__.get(f.name)
            for f in self.__dataclass_fields__.values()
        }

    def __getattribute__(self, name):
        """Return explicit value or worker default.

        Only worker-scoped runtime fields participate in
        this fallback.
        """
        if name in WORKER_DEFAULT_ATTRIBUTES:
            raw = object.__getattribute__(
                self, "__dict__"
            ).get(name)
            if raw is None:
                worker = object.__getattribute__(
                    self, "__dict__"
                ).get("who") or default_username
                default = get_worker_default(
                    worker, name
                )
                if default is not None:
                    return default
        return object.__getattribute__(self, name)

    @classmethod
    def from_dict(cls, data: dict) -> "TodoItem":
        """Create from dictionary (JSON deserialization).

        Unknown keys are silently ignored for forward
        compatibility. Missing priority keeps the legacy
        default of [[0.0]], while an explicit JSON null is
        preserved as an unset priority.
        """
        known = {f.name for f in cls.__dataclass_fields__.values()}
        filtered = {k: v for k, v in data.items() if k in known}
        return cls(**filtered)
@

