\section{Effective Priority}

The effective priority determines display and scheduling order for
ranked items. Without a deadline, it equals the base priority. With a
deadline, we add a boost that increases quadratically as the deadline
approaches.

Some items are intentionally left unranked. They still need a stable
display order, but they should not participate in numeric midpoint
math. We therefore let [[effective_priority]] return [[None]] when the
stored priority is unset, and handle mixed ranked/unranked lists with a
separate display-order helper.

Why quadratic rather than linear? A linear curve would start boosting
immediately, which is unhelpful for items due in three months. The
quadratic curve stays near zero until roughly the last third of the
time span, then ramps up sharply---matching the human experience of
\enquote{it's not urgent yet} followed by \enquote{this is due soon!}

<<effective priority>>=
def effective_priority(
    item: TodoItem,
    now: datetime.datetime | None = None,
) -> float | None:
    """Compute effective priority including deadline boost.

    Returns ``None`` when the stored base priority is
    unset. Otherwise returns base priority plus a
    deadline-based urgency boost that increases
    quadratically as the deadline approaches.
    """
    if now is None:
        now = datetime.datetime.now()

    if item.priority is None:
        return None

    base = item.priority

    if not item.deadline:
        return base

    deadline_dt = datetime.datetime.fromisoformat(
        item.deadline
    )
    created_dt = datetime.datetime.fromisoformat(
        item.created
    )

    max_boost = get_max_boost()

    days_remaining = (deadline_dt - now).total_seconds() / 86400
    total_span = max(
        (deadline_dt - created_dt).total_seconds() / 86400,
        1.0,
    )

    if days_remaining <= 0:
        return base + max_boost

    urgency = max(0.0, 1.0 - days_remaining / total_span)
    deadline_boost = max_boost * (urgency ** 2)

    return base + deadline_boost


def require_effective_priority(
    item: TodoItem,
    now: datetime.datetime | None = None,
) -> float:
    """Return effective priority for a ranked item."""
    priority = effective_priority(item, now)
    if priority is None:
        raise ValueError(
            f"todo #{item.id} has no numeric priority"
        )
    return priority


def todo_display_sort_key(
    item: TodoItem,
    now: datetime.datetime | None = None,
) -> tuple:
    """Return the user-facing display-order key.

    Ranked items sort before unranked ones. Among the
    unranked tail, earlier deadlines come first and
    items without deadlines come last.
    """
    priority = effective_priority(item, now)
    if priority is not None:
        return (
            0,
            -priority,
            item.created or "",
            item.id,
        )
    return (
        1,
        item.deadline is None,
        item.deadline or "",
        item.created or "",
        item.id,
    )


def sort_todos_for_display(
    items: list[TodoItem],
    now: datetime.datetime | None = None,
) -> list[TodoItem]:
    """Return todos in the shared display order."""
    return sorted(
        items,
        key=lambda item: todo_display_sort_key(item, now),
    )
@

\subsection{Testing Effective Priority}

We verify the key properties: no boost without deadline, zero boost
when deadline is far away, maximum boost when deadline is past, and
quadratic growth in between.

<<test functions>>=
def test_effective_priority_no_deadline():
    """Without a deadline, effective equals base priority."""
    item = TodoItem(
        id=1, title="Test", priority=5.0,
        created="2026-01-01T00:00:00"
    )
    assert effective_priority(item) == 5.0


def test_effective_priority_past_deadline():
    """Past-deadline items get maximum boost."""
    item = TodoItem(
        id=1, title="Test", priority=5.0,
        created="2026-01-01T00:00:00",
        deadline="2026-01-15T00:00:00",
    )
    now = datetime.datetime(2026, 1, 20)
    result = effective_priority(item, now)
    assert result == 5.0 + DEFAULT_MAX_BOOST


def test_effective_priority_unset_priority():
    """Unranked items have no effective priority score."""
    item = TodoItem(
        id=1,
        title="Unranked",
        priority=None,
        created="2026-01-01T00:00:00",
    )
    assert effective_priority(item) is None


def test_effective_priority_quadratic_growth():
    """Boost should be small early and large near deadline."""
    item = TodoItem(
        id=1, title="Test", priority=0.0,
        created="2026-01-01T00:00:00",
        deadline="2026-01-31T00:00:00",
    )
    early = datetime.datetime(2026, 1, 5)
    mid = datetime.datetime(2026, 1, 20)
    late = datetime.datetime(2026, 1, 29)

    p_early = effective_priority(item, early)
    p_mid = effective_priority(item, mid)
    p_late = effective_priority(item, late)

    assert p_early < p_mid < p_late
    # Early boost should be small (quadratic)
    assert p_early < 1.0


def test_sort_todos_for_display_keeps_unranked_tail():
    """Unranked items sort after ranked ones by deadline."""
    ranked = TodoItem(
        id=1,
        title="Ranked",
        priority=5.0,
        created="2026-01-01T00:00:00",
    )
    early = TodoItem(
        id=2,
        title="Early deadline",
        priority=None,
        created="2026-01-02T00:00:00",
        deadline="2026-01-10T00:00:00",
    )
    late = TodoItem(
        id=3,
        title="Late deadline",
        priority=None,
        created="2026-01-03T00:00:00",
        deadline="2026-01-20T00:00:00",
    )
    someday = TodoItem(
        id=4,
        title="No deadline",
        priority=None,
        created="2026-01-04T00:00:00",
    )

    ordered = sort_todos_for_display([
        late,
        someday,
        ranked,
        early,
    ])

    assert [item.id for item in ordered] == [1, 2, 3, 4]
