\section{Active Task Stack}

The todo system supports nested work: start a parent task, decompose
it into sub-tasks, work on children one at a time.  To track
\emph{which} task is innermost-active, we maintain an active stack of
todo IDs in [[active_stack.json]].

The active stack is the authority for execution state.  A todo is
[[in-progress]] iff its ID is present in the stack; otherwise it is
either [[pending]] or [[done]].  We still store [[status]] in
[[todos.json]] because many commands filter or display it, but we treat
that field as derived data and re-synchronize it from the active stack
whenever the todo state changes.

We keep the stack in a separate file because it models a different kind
of state: ephemeral execution context rather than task metadata.  That
separation is still useful, but it must not create a second source of
truth.  We therefore mutate [[todos.json]] and [[active_stack.json]]
together under a single lock.

The stack obeys LIFO discipline:
\begin{description}
\item[Push] [[todo start <id>]] appends to the stack.
\item[Pop] [[todo done]] (no argument) pops the top and marks
  it done.
\item[Remove] [[todo done <id>]] removes that specific ID from
  anywhere in the stack.
\end{description}

Those rules are easy to state but tricky to preserve under concurrent
commands.  The helper layer below therefore does more than basic file
I/O: it normalizes stale state, synchronizes derived fields, and applies
mutations under one lock so that both JSON files move together.

<<active stack helpers>>=
def get_todo_lock_file() -> pathlib.Path:
    """Return the todo-state lock file path."""
    return get_todo_dir() / "todo.lock"


def get_active_stack_file() -> pathlib.Path:
    """Return path to the active-task stack file."""
    return get_todo_dir() / "active_stack.json"


def normalize_active_stack(
    todos: list[TodoItem], stack: list[int]
) -> list[int]:
    """Return a deduplicated active stack consistent with todos."""
    todo_by_id = {item.id: item for item in todos}
    seen = set()
    normalized = []
    for todo_id in stack:
        item = todo_by_id.get(todo_id)
        if item is None or item.status == "done":
            continue
        if todo_id in seen:
            continue
        normalized.append(todo_id)
        seen.add(todo_id)
    return normalized
@


Normalization performs only structural repair: remove missing or done
IDs and collapse duplicates while preserving order.  That keeps the
stack usable even after an interrupted command, without silently
inventing new active work.

<<active stack helpers>>=
def synchronize_todo_statuses(
    todos: list[TodoItem], stack: list[int]
):
    """Make [[status]] match the authoritative active stack."""
    active_ids = set(stack)
    for item in todos:
        if item.status == "done":
            continue
        if item.id in active_ids:
            item.status = "in-progress"
        else:
            item.status = "pending"
@


The stored [[status]] field is now a cache of stack membership rather
than an independent authority.  We preserve [[done]] exactly as written,
but every non-done item is reclassified from the active stack before the
rest of the CLI sees it.

<<active stack helpers>>=
def load_todos_raw() -> tuple:
    """Load todos without synchronizing derived state."""
    todo_file = get_todo_file()
    if not todo_file.exists():
        return 1, []

    try:
        with open(todo_file, "r") as f:
            data = json.load(f)
            todos = [
                TodoItem.from_dict(t)
                for t in data.get("todos", [])
            ]
            return data.get("next_id", 1), todos
    except (
        json.JSONDecodeError,
        KeyError,
        ValueError,
    ) as e:
        logging.warning(
            f"Error loading todos from {todo_file}: {e}"
        )
        return 1, []


def load_active_stack_raw() -> list[int]:
    """Load the active stack without consulting [[todos.json]]."""
    stack_file = get_active_stack_file()
    if not stack_file.exists():
        return []
    try:
        with open(stack_file) as f:
            data = json.load(f)
        if isinstance(data, list):
            return [int(todo_id) for todo_id in data]
        return []
    except (json.JSONDecodeError, OSError, ValueError):
        return []
@


The raw loaders above do not attempt to reconcile the two files.  That
job belongs to [[load_todo_state]], which combines them into one coherent
view before handing data to command logic.

<<active stack helpers>>=
def load_todo_state() -> tuple:
    """Load todos and active stack with synchronized status."""
    next_id, todos = load_todos_raw()
    stack = normalize_active_stack(
        todos, load_active_stack_raw()
    )
    synchronize_todo_statuses(todos, stack)
    return next_id, todos, stack
@


Once we have a coherent in-memory state, writes should either fully
succeed or leave the old files untouched.  We therefore use
temporary-file writes followed by [[os.replace]], which gives atomic
replacement on the local filesystem.

<<active stack helpers>>=
def write_json_atomically(
    path: pathlib.Path,
    data,
    *,
    indent: int | None = None,
):
    """Write JSON data atomically to [[path]]."""
    ensure_todo_dir()
    fd, tmp_name = tempfile.mkstemp(
        prefix=f"{path.name}-",
        suffix=".tmp",
        dir=str(path.parent),
    )
    os.close(fd)
    try:
        with open(tmp_name, "w") as f:
            json.dump(data, f, indent=indent)
            f.flush()
            os.fsync(f.fileno())
        os.replace(tmp_name, path)
    finally:
        if os.path.exists(tmp_name):
            os.unlink(tmp_name)


def save_todo_state_unlocked(
    next_id: int,
    todos: list[TodoItem],
    stack: list[int],
):
    """Persist todos and active stack after synchronization."""
    normalized_stack = normalize_active_stack(todos, stack)
    synchronize_todo_statuses(todos, normalized_stack)
    write_json_atomically(
        get_todo_file(),
        {
            "next_id": next_id,
            "todos": [t.to_dict() for t in todos],
        },
        indent=2,
    )
    write_json_atomically(
        get_active_stack_file(),
        normalized_stack,
    )
@


Atomic file replacement is still not enough on its own: two processes
could each compute a valid next state from the same old snapshot and the
later writer would erase the earlier one.  [[mutate_todo_state]] solves
that by acquiring an exclusive lock around the entire read-modify-write
cycle.

<<active stack helpers>>=
def mutate_todo_state(callback):
    """Mutate todos and active stack under one lock."""
    ensure_todo_dir()
    lock_file = get_todo_lock_file()
    with open(lock_file, "w") as lock_handle:
        fcntl.flock(lock_handle, fcntl.LOCK_EX)
        try:
            next_id, todos, stack = load_todo_state()
            callback_result = callback(next_id, todos, stack)
            if callback_result is None:
                updated_next_id = next_id
                updated_todos = todos
                updated_stack = stack
                extra = ()
            else:
                updated_next_id = callback_result[0]
                updated_todos = callback_result[1]
                updated_stack = callback_result[2]
                extra = callback_result[3:]
            save_todo_state_unlocked(
                updated_next_id,
                updated_todos,
                updated_stack,
            )
            if extra:
                return (
                    updated_next_id,
                    updated_todos,
                    normalize_active_stack(
                        updated_todos, updated_stack
                    ),
                    *extra,
                )
            return (
                updated_next_id,
                updated_todos,
                normalize_active_stack(
                    updated_todos, updated_stack
                ),
            )
        finally:
            fcntl.flock(lock_handle, fcntl.LOCK_UN)


def load_active_stack() -> list[int]:
    """Load the stack of active todo IDs.

    Returns an empty list if the file doesn't exist.
    """
    _, _, stack = load_todo_state()
    return stack


def save_active_stack(stack: list[int]):
    """Save the active-task stack to persistent storage."""
    def update(next_id, todos, _stack):
        return next_id, todos, stack

    mutate_todo_state(update)
