\section{Sub-item Helpers}

Sub-items create a tree structure within the flat todo list. We need
helpers to navigate this tree: finding children, finding siblings (for
priority comparison), and checking whether a parent's children are all
done.

Why store sub-items flat with [[parent_id]] rather than nesting them?
Because flat storage simplifies JSON serialization, avoids recursive
data structures, and lets commands like [[todo ls --flat]] work
without flattening logic.

Priority comparison uses siblings---items sharing the same parent.
When multiple workers share a parent (say a course-level epic), each
worker's priorities are independent: it makes no sense to ask
\enquote{is your grading task more urgent than my lecture-prep task?}
The optional [[who]] parameter on [[get_active_siblings]] restricts
the comparison set to a single worker so that binary-search
prioritisation stays meaningful.

The active stack is global (all workers share one
[[active_stack.json]]), but stack-based commands like [[stop]] and
[[done]] should operate on the current worker's topmost item, not
another worker's. [[filter_ids_by_worker]] narrows a list of todo IDs
to those belonging to a given worker, treating [[who=None]] as
[[default_username]] for backward compatibility with older items.

<<sub-item helpers>>=
def get_children(
    todos: list[TodoItem], parent_id: int
) -> list[TodoItem]:
    """Get all direct children of a todo item."""
    return [t for t in todos if t.parent_id == parent_id]


def get_siblings(
    todos: list[TodoItem], item: TodoItem
) -> list[TodoItem]:
    """Get siblings of an item (same parent level).

    For top-level items, siblings are all other top-level
    items. For sub-items, siblings share the same parent.
    """
    return [
        t
        for t in todos
        if t.parent_id == item.parent_id and t.id != item.id
    ]
@

The [[add]], [[reprioritize]], and [[import]] commands compare a
todo against its siblings to place it in the priority order.
When multiple workers share a parent, the comparison set must be
restricted to one worker's items; otherwise the binary search
would ask the user to rank unrelated tasks against each other.
The [[who]] filter is applied inside the list comprehension so
that the sort operates only on the relevant subset.

<<sub-item helpers>>=
def get_active_siblings(
    todos: list[TodoItem],
    item: TodoItem,
    who: str | None = None,
    ranked_only: bool = False,
) -> list[TodoItem]:
    """Get pending/in-progress siblings in the shared
    priority order.

    When ``who`` is given, only siblings assigned to
    that worker are returned. When ``ranked_only`` is
    true, siblings with unset priorities are excluded.
    """
    siblings = get_siblings(todos, item)
    active = [
        s
        for s in siblings
        if s.status != "done"
        and (
            who is None
            or (s.who or default_username) == who
        )
    ]
    if ranked_only:
        active = [
            s for s in active
            if s.priority is not None
        ]
        active.sort(
            key=require_effective_priority,
            reverse=True,
        )
    else:
        active = sort_todos_for_display(active)
    return active
@

The active stack ([[active_stack.json]]) is global---all workers
push and pop on the same list.  Stack-based commands like [[stop]]
and [[done]] need to ignore entries that belong to other workers,
otherwise one worker's implicit resolution would land on another
worker's item.  [[filter_ids_by_worker]] performs that narrowing.
Items created before the [[who]] field existed have
[[who=None]]; we treat those as belonging to
[[default_username]] so they remain reachable.

<<sub-item helpers>>=
def filter_ids_by_worker(
    todos: list[TodoItem],
    ids: list[int],
    who: str,
) -> list[int]:
    """Keep only todo IDs belonging to ``who``.

    Treats items with ``who=None`` as belonging to
    ``default_username``.
    """
    by_id = {t.id: t for t in todos}
    return [
        i
        for i in ids
        if i in by_id
        and (by_id[i].who or default_username) == who
    ]


def todo_depth(
    todos: list[TodoItem],
    item: TodoItem,
) -> int:
    """Return the depth of ``item`` in the todo tree."""
    by_id = {t.id: t for t in todos}
    depth = 0
    seen = set()
    parent_id = item.parent_id
    while (
        parent_id is not None
        and parent_id in by_id
        and parent_id not in seen
    ):
        seen.add(parent_id)
        depth += 1
        parent_id = by_id[parent_id].parent_id
    return depth


def check_parent_completion(
    todos: list[TodoItem], parent_id: int
) -> bool:
    """Check if all children of a parent are done.

    Returns True if the parent has children and all are
    done. Returns False if there are no children or any
    child is not done.
    """
    children = get_children(todos, parent_id)
    if not children:
        return False
    return all(c.status == "done" for c in children)
@

The [[next]] command and the cron script both need to find the
highest-priority pending task, optionally scoped to a specific
parent.  Extracting this into a function (rather than a reusable
chunk) makes the dependency on [[todos]] and [[who]] explicit
through parameters.  The worker filter follows the same backward-
compatibility rule as the active stack: older items with [[who=None]]
still count as belonging to [[default_username]].

<<sub-item helpers>>=
def find_pending_by_priority(
    todos: list[TodoItem],
    who: str | None = None,
    parent_id: int | None = None,
) -> TodoItem | None:
    """Find highest-priority pending task.

    Optionally filtered by assignee regex and parent.
    Treats ``who=None`` as ``default_username``.
    Returns None if no matching task is found.
    """
    candidates = [
        t for t in todos
        if t.status == "pending"
        and (parent_id is None
             or t.parent_id == parent_id)
    ]
    if who:
        candidates = [
            t for t in candidates
            if re.search(
                who, t.who or default_username
            )
        ]
    now = datetime.datetime.now()
    candidates.sort(
        key=lambda item: todo_display_sort_key(item, now)
    )
    return candidates[0] if candidates else None
@

Status reporting and auto-parenting both read the authoritative active
stack, but they need different views of it.  [[status]] needs every
active item in stack order so it can render a forest of active
hierarchies.  [[next]], [[add]], and [[import]] instead need a single
leaf: the active todo for the current tmux and worker context.  Keeping
those helpers separate prevents the old single-chain model from leaking
back in.

For commands that operate on the current user's own work, the fallback
must prefer that worker's active entry outside tmux when one exists.
Otherwise another worker's later stack entry would steal implicit
resolution for [[next]], [[add]], or [[import]].  But we cannot require
such an entry: when only one foreign-worker task is active, the old
single-stack behaviour should still resolve to that task.

<<sub-item helpers>>=
def get_active_todos(
    todos: list[TodoItem],
) -> list[TodoItem]:
    """Return active todos in normalized stack order."""
    by_id = {item.id: item for item in todos}
    stack = load_active_stack()
    return [by_id[todo_id] for todo_id in stack if todo_id in by_id]


def get_current_context_todo(
    todos: list[TodoItem],
    who: str | None = default_username,
) -> TodoItem | None:
    """Return the active todo for the current context.

    When tmux labels identify one of several parallel active
    hierarchies, return the deepest active todo in that context.
    Inside tmux without a tracked local todo, return
    ``None`` rather than inheriting another window's
    branch. Outside tmux, catch the tmux-specific
    lookup error and prefer that worker's active-stack
    top, falling back to the plain active-stack top
    when the worker has no active entry.
    """
    by_id = {item.id: item for item in todos}
    stack = load_active_stack()
    if not stack:
        return None
    try:
        context_id = resolve_todo_from_tmux_context(
            who or default_username, stack,
        )
    except NotInTmuxError:
        context_id = None
        in_tmux = False
    else:
        in_tmux = True
    if in_tmux and context_id is None:
        return None
    if context_id is not None:
        resolved_id = context_id
    elif who is not None:
        worker_stack = filter_ids_by_worker(
            todos, stack, who,
        )
        resolved_id = (
            worker_stack[-1]
            if worker_stack else stack[-1]
        )
    else:
        resolved_id = stack[-1]
    return by_id.get(resolved_id)
