    assert "#1" in result.output

    stack = load_active_stack()
    assert 1 not in stack
    assert 5 in stack
@

Completion combines resolution, marking the item done, and
removing it from the stack in a single locked mutation.

An explicit completion target needs one extra check beyond
[[resolve_todo_id]].  Stack filtering is enough when the ID is omitted,
but an explicit ID must still belong to the chosen worker; otherwise
[[todo done 17]] could silently mutate another worker's task merely
because todo IDs are global.  We therefore factor the read-only lookup
into [[resolve_done_target]] so the preflight descendant guard and the
locked state mutation share the same ownership rule.

<<helpers>>=
def resolve_done_target(todo_id, todos, who=None):
    """Resolve a completion target in one worker context."""
    resolved_id = resolve_todo_id(
        todo_id, "mark done",
        who=who, todos=todos,
    )
    item = next(
        (t for t in todos if t.id == resolved_id),
        None,
    )
    if item is None:
        typer.echo(
            f"Error: todo #{resolved_id} not found",
            err=True,
        )
        raise typer.Exit(1)
    owner = item.who or default_username
    if who is not None and owner != who:
        typer.echo(
            f"Error: todo #{resolved_id} belongs to "
            f"{owner}. Pass --who {owner} to mark done.",
            err=True,
        )
        raise typer.Exit(1)
    return resolved_id, item


def complete_todo_state(todo_id, who=None):
    """Mark a todo done and remove it from the active stack."""

    def update(next_id, todos, stack):
        resolved_id, item = resolve_done_target(
            todo_id, todos, who=who
        )
        item.status = "done"
        stack = [sid for sid in stack if sid != resolved_id]
        return next_id, todos, stack, resolved_id, item

    next_id, todos, stack, resolved_id, item = apply_todo_mutation(update)
    return resolved_id, item, next_id, todos, stack
@

When all children of a parent become done, the parent is auto-completed.
This runs as a separate locked mutation so that tracking labels can be
stopped between the child completion and the parent status change.

The new worker-scoped completion rules add one guard here.  A worker may
complete only that worker's branch, so auto-completion must not let the
last child completed for one worker silently mark another worker's
parent done.  We therefore thread the resolved worker context into the
helper and stop at the boundary when the parent belongs to someone else.

<<helpers>>=
def auto_complete_parent(item, todos, who=None):
    """Auto-complete the parent if all siblings are done.

    Runs a second locked mutation so tracking labels
    are stopped before the parent status changes.
    When ``who`` is given, only parents owned by that
    worker are auto-completed.
    """
    if item.parent_id is None:
        return
    if not check_parent_completion(todos, item.parent_id):
        return
    parent_item = next(
        (t for t in todos if t.id == item.parent_id),
        None,
    )
    if parent_item is None or parent_item.status == "done":
        return
    resolved_who = who
    if resolved_who is None:
        resolved_who = item.who or default_username
    if (
        parent_item.who or default_username
    ) != resolved_who:
        return

    stop_todo_tracking(parent_item.id, parent_item, todos)

    def mark_parent(next_id, todos, stack):
        parent = next(
            (t for t in todos
             if t.id == item.parent_id),
            None,
        )
        if parent and parent.status != "done":
            parent.status = "done"
            typer.echo(
                f"  Parent #{parent.id} "
                f"auto-completed: {parent.title}"
            )
        return next_id, todos, stack

    mutate_todo_state(mark_parent)
@

\subsubsection{Auto-activating Ancestors}

The converse of auto-completing a parent is auto-activating one.  When a
user starts a child directly ([[todo start 7]] where~7 is a sub-item of
parent~5), the parent should already be on the active stack---otherwise
the hierarchy reported by [[todo status]] would be incomplete, and
tracking would miss the parent's labels entirely.

Rather than requiring the user to manually start every ancestor first, we
walk up the [[parent_id]] chain and activate any ancestor that is not
already on the stack.  We collect ancestors from the child upward, then
reverse the list so that the outermost ancestor is pushed first, giving
the stack the correct root-to-leaf order.

Each activated ancestor also gets its labels tracked.  Without this, the
parent would appear in the hierarchy but accumulate no time---defeating
the purpose of nested tracking.  We reuse the same
[[start_tracking_labels]] path that [[<<start tracking via track module>>]]
uses for the explicitly started item.

Tmux launches need one extra rule.  When [[todo start --pane]] or
[[todo start --window]] is about to create a new tracked tmux context, the
generic current-shell tmux update would target the source pane or window
instead of the newly launched one.  We therefore thread an
[[update_tmux_context]] flag through ancestor activation so tmux launches
can mirror [[track start]] and let [[run_tmux_command()]] publish the
authoritative pane or window state.

<<helpers>>=
def ensure_ancestors_active(
    item, todos, stack, *,
    update_tmux_context=True,
):
    """Activate and track all ancestors of ``item``.

    Walks up the parent chain and, for each ancestor
    not already on the active stack, pushes it onto
    the stack and starts tracking its labels.

    Returns the list of ancestor items that were
    newly activated (outermost first).
    """
    by_id = {t.id: t for t in todos}
    missing = []
    current = item
    while current.parent_id is not None:
        parent = by_id.get(current.parent_id)
        if parent is None:
            break
        if parent.id not in stack:
            missing.append(parent)
        current = parent

    if not missing:
        return []

    missing.reverse()

    def push_ancestors(next_id, todos, stack):
        for ancestor in missing:
            if ancestor.id not in stack:
                idx = stack.index(item.id) \
                    if item.id in stack else len(stack)
                stack.insert(idx, ancestor.id)
        return next_id, todos, stack

    mutate_todo_state(push_ancestors)

    try:
        from nytid.cli.track import (
            start_tracking_labels,
        )
        worker = item.who or default_username
        for ancestor in missing:
            labels = list(ancestor.labels) + [
                f"todo:{ancestor.id}"
            ]
            started, _, _ = start_tracking_labels(
                labels,
                start_time=datetime.datetime.now(),
                who=worker,
                update_tmux_context=update_tmux_context,
            )
            typer.echo(
                f"  Auto-started parent: "
                f"#{ancestor.id} {ancestor.title}"
            )
            if started:
                typer.echo(
                    f"  Tracking: "
                    f"{', '.join(sorted(started))}"
                )
    except ImportError:
        pass

    return missing
@

