Now the implementation. We first reject contradictory flags, then
resolve the parent ID, determine the priority, and finally save.

<<add command implementation>>=
next_id, todos = load_todos()

<<validate add options>>

if edit_mode:
    <<add via editor>>
else:
    <<add via cli flags>>
@

Some combinations would give contradictory instructions. In
particular, [[--prio]] says 
\enquote{use exactly this numeric value} while
[[--append]] says 
\enquote{derive a value by placing the item after its
siblings}. Rather than silently picking one interpretation, we reject
the combination and ask the user to choose.  [[--skip-priority]] is also
exclusive with both numeric modes: either we store a number now, or we
store no number and leave the item for later ranking:

<<validate add options>>=
if explicit_priority is not None and append:
    typer.echo(
        "Error: --prio and --append cannot be used together",
        err=True,
    )
    raise typer.Exit(1)
if skip_priority and explicit_priority is not None:
    typer.echo(
        "Error: --skip-priority and --prio cannot be "
        "used together",
        err=True,
    )
    raise typer.Exit(1)
if skip_priority and append:
    typer.echo(
        "Error: --skip-priority and --append cannot be "
        "used together",
        err=True,
    )
    raise typer.Exit(1)
@

The CLI-flag path is the original flow: resolve parent, determine the
priority, create a single item.  We copy [[title]] into
[[priority_title]] because the priority-resolution chunk is shared
with the editor path, where [[title]] is not yet set; both paths
provide the display name through [[priority_title]] instead.

The implicit parent comes from the operator's current active context,
not from the assignee of the new todo.  That lets us add or import a
child for someone else while still nesting it under the branch we are
currently working in.

<<add via cli flags>>=
if not title:
    typer.echo(
        "Error: --title is required "
        "(or use --edit)",
        err=True,
    )
    raise typer.Exit(1)
priority_title = title
<<resolve parent id>>
<<inherit from parent>>
<<resolve priority for new todo>>
<<create and save new todo>>
