Auto-parenting: if no explicit parent is given and we're not forcing
top-level, reuse the current active todo for the current tmux context:

When tmux is active but the current pane/window has no tracked todo,
that means there is no local parent to inherit, so the new item stays
top-level.

<<resolve parent id>>=
resolved_parent = parent
if parent is None and not top_level:
    active = get_current_context_todo(todos)
    if active is not None:
        resolved_parent = active.id
        typer.echo(
            f"Auto-parenting under: "
            f"#{active.id} {active.title}"
        )
@

When a parent is set, inherit its deadline and labels unless the user
explicitly provided overrides:

<<inherit from parent>>=
inherited_labels = list(label) if label else []
inherited_deadline = deadline
if resolved_parent is not None:
    parent_item = next(
        (t for t in todos if t.id == resolved_parent),
        None,
    )
    if parent_item is None:
        typer.echo(
            f"Error: parent #{resolved_parent} not found",
            err=True,
        )
        raise typer.Exit(1)
    if not label and parent_item.labels:
        inherited_labels = list(parent_item.labels)
    if deadline is None and parent_item.deadline:
        inherited_deadline = parent_item.deadline
@

Priority selection has three modes. [[--prio]] bypasses all inference.
[[--append]] keeps the operation non-interactive by placing the item at
the bottom of the current sibling list. Otherwise we fall back to the
interactive binary search, which remains the default because it
preserves the existing 
\enquote{compare against nearby tasks} workflow.  In all three modes
the sibling set is scoped to the target worker ([[--who]]) so that
priorities stay meaningful within one person's task list.

[[--skip-priority]] is the one exception: it deliberately bypasses all
numeric placement and stores [[None]] instead.

An unranked parent is an even stronger constraint.  Until the parent
itself has a numeric priority there is no child interval to place new
work into, so every newly added child stays unranked regardless of
whether the caller asked for [[--prio]], [[--append]], or the default
interactive comparison.

The append path works from stored base priorities, not
[[effective_priority]].  Deadline boost is intentionally temporary; if we
reused an effective score as a newly stored base priority, an urgent
sibling could donate its temporary boost to the appended item and change
the long-term ordering.

The empty-sibling case under a parent is different.  There the child
range is still completely unused, so 
placing the first child at the midpoint is not a failure to append.
Instead it preserves room on both sides for later siblings, mirroring
the same 
binary-search insertion strategy we use elsewhere: the first placement
creates a balanced starting point, and later children can still be added
above or below it without forcing an early renumbering.

<<resolve priority for new todo>>=
# Build a candidate item once so sibling lookup and interactive
# comparison show the same context everywhere.
candidate = TodoItem(
    id=0,
    title=priority_title,
    parent_id=resolved_parent,
    labels=inherited_labels,
    deadline=inherited_deadline,
    estimated=(
        parse_hours(estimate) if estimate else None
    ),
)
siblings = get_active_siblings(
    todos, candidate, who=who, ranked_only=True,
)
parent_ctx = (
    parent_item if resolved_parent is not None
    else None
)
if parent_ctx is not None and parent_ctx.priority is None:
    priority = None
elif skip_priority:
    priority = None
elif explicit_priority is not None:
    priority = explicit_priority
elif append:
    if siblings:
        priority = append_priority_after_siblings(
            siblings
        )
    elif parent_ctx is not None:
        high, low = compute_child_priority_range(
            todos, parent_ctx
        )
        priority = (high + low) / 2.0
    else:
        priority = 1.0
else:
    priority = binary_search_priority(
        siblings,
        candidate,
        parent=parent_ctx, todos=todos,
    )
@

When [[--here]] is used, we capture the current working directory and
the full environment---just like UNIX [[at]].  The separate [[--wd]]
and [[--env]] flags let the user update only one side of that context.
If several are supplied, [[--here]] simply provides defaults that the
more specific flags can still override.

\paragraph{Canonicalizing the working directory.}
Whichever flag supplies the [[wd]] string, the resulting value is
persisted to disk and later replayed by [[todo start]], possibly from
a completely unrelated working directory---a systemd unit, a different
shell, or an automation worker.  This means relative paths and [[~]]
references must be resolved \emph{at write time}: at read time we have
no way to reconstruct the shell cwd or the user's home directory as
they were when the todo was created.  We therefore route every
[[wd]]-accepting write site through a single helper, so that
CLI-sourced strings and YAML-sourced strings from the [[--edit]] path
both obey the same invariant---persisted [[wd]] is always an absolute,
tilde-expanded, canonical path.

Composing [[expanduser]] with [[abspath]] is idempotent on
already-canonical paths, so the helper is safe to apply uniformly on
both kinds of input: the shell usually expands [[~]] before the CLI
string ever reaches Python, whereas strings typed into the YAML editor
buffer have had no such expansion.  We reject non-string input
defensively because our minimal YAML parser (see
[[parse_yaml_value]]) returns an [[int]] when the user types
[[wd: 42]], and passing that straight to [[os.path.expanduser]]
produces a confusing [[TypeError]] from deep inside [[os.path]].  A
clear [[typer.Exit]] surfaces the mistake at the exact line of user
input instead.

<<helpers>>=
def canonicalize_wd(wd):
    """Return ``wd`` as an absolute, tilde-expanded path.

    Returns ``None`` for ``None`` or empty string.
    Exits with an error on non-string, non-``None``
    input such as an ``int`` parsed from a stray
    ``wd: 42`` line in YAML front matter.
    """
    if wd is None or wd == "":
        return None
    if not isinstance(wd, str):
        typer.echo(
            f"Error: wd must be a string, "
            f"got {type(wd).__name__}: {wd!r}",
            err=True,
        )
        raise typer.Exit(1)
    return os.path.abspath(
        os.path.expanduser(wd)
    )
@

Let's verify the helper handles the four interesting cases: a
relative path resolves against the current directory, a tilde
reference expands to the home directory, a bare tilde expands to
the home directory on its own, and a non-string input produces a
clean error instead of a [[TypeError]].

<<test functions>>=
def test_canonicalize_wd_resolves_relative(
    tmp_path, monkeypatch,
):
    """canonicalize_wd turns '.' into an absolute path."""
    monkeypatch.chdir(tmp_path)
    assert canonicalize_wd(".") == str(tmp_path)


def test_canonicalize_wd_expands_tilde():
    """canonicalize_wd expands '~/foo' against $HOME."""
    assert canonicalize_wd("~/foo") == os.path.join(
        os.path.expanduser("~"), "foo",
    )


def test_canonicalize_wd_expands_bare_tilde():
    """canonicalize_wd expands '~' alone to the home dir."""
    assert canonicalize_wd("~") == os.path.expanduser("~")


def test_canonicalize_wd_none_and_empty():
    """canonicalize_wd returns None for None or ''."""
    assert canonicalize_wd(None) is None
    assert canonicalize_wd("") is None


def test_canonicalize_wd_rejects_non_string():
    """canonicalize_wd rejects non-string input cleanly."""
    with pytest.raises(typer.Exit):
        canonicalize_wd(42)
@

With the helper in place, the resolve step simply routes the CLI
[[wd_path]] through it.  The [[os.getcwd()]] branch used by
