\subsubsection{Adding via Editor}

When [[--edit]] is used, the editor opens with the title pre-filled
(if given on the command line). Any CLI flags such as [[--deadline]],
[[--estimate]], and [[--wd]], along with positional labels, are
rendered as a YAML
front\-matter block so the user can review and adjust them before
saving. Without this pre-population the flags would still take effect
(they are merged in [[<<create parent from parsed>>]]), but the user
would never see them in the editor---a confusing silent override.

We intentionally do 
not render [[--env]] into the editor preamble: a captured process
environment is often large, noisy, and not something the user wants to
edit as front matter.  The flag still applies when saving, just without
dumping the whole environment into the buffer.

<<add via editor>>=
<<build initial editor metadata>>
initial = title if title else ""
yaml_header = render_yaml_block(initial_meta)
if yaml_header:
    initial = initial + "\n" + yaml_header
content = open_editor(initial + "\n")
parsed = parse_editor_content(content)
if not parsed.title:
    typer.echo("No title provided.", err=True)
    raise typer.Exit(1)

priority_title = parsed.title
<<resolve parent id>>
<<inherit from parent>>
<<resolve priority for new todo>>
<<create parent from parsed>>
<<create children from parsed>>
save_todos(next_id, todos)
@

We build a metadata dictionary from CLI flags so the editor opens
with a pre-populated YAML block. The key names match those used by
[[parse_yaml_block]] and [[build_item_metadata]], ensuring
round-trip consistency. We omit keys whose values are empty to keep
the editor uncluttered.

We always emit [[who]] even when it matches [[default_username]].
This serves two purposes: it makes the assignment explicit so the
user can see who will own the task, and --- crucially --- it
reminds the user of the exact attribute name when they want to
assign a sub-item to someone else.  Without a visible [[who:]]
key in the parent block, a user adding children has no obvious
cue that children can carry their own [[who]] field.

<<build initial editor metadata>>=
initial_meta = {}
if label:
    initial_meta["labels"] = list(label)
if deadline:
    initial_meta["deadline"] = deadline
if estimate:
    initial_meta["estimate"] = parse_hours(estimate)
if who:
    initial_meta["who"] = who
if wd_path:
    initial_meta["wd"] = canonicalize_wd(wd_path)
elif here:
    initial_meta["wd"] = os.getcwd()
if run_command:
    initial_meta["command"] = run_command
@

We apply metadata from the YAML front matter to the parent item,
with CLI flags taking precedence where provided:

<<create parent from parsed>>=
now = datetime.datetime.now().isoformat()
meta = parsed.metadata
resolved_wd = canonicalize_wd(meta.get("wd")) or (
    os.getcwd() if here else None
)
resolved_env = None
if wd_path:
    resolved_wd = canonicalize_wd(wd_path)
if here:
    resolved_env = dict(os.environ)
elif capture_env:
    resolved_env = dict(os.environ)
parent_item = TodoItem(
    id=next_id,
    title=parsed.title,
    labels=(
        list(label) if label
        else meta.get("labels", [])
    ),
    priority=priority,
    status="pending",
    created=now,
    deadline=deadline or meta.get("deadline"),
    estimated=(
        parse_hours(estimate)
        if estimate
        else meta.get("estimate")
    ),
    description=description or "",
    parent_id=resolved_parent,
    who=who or meta.get("who"),
    notes=parsed.notes,
    wd=resolved_wd,
    env=resolved_env,
    command=(
        run_command or meta.get("command")
    ),
)
todos.append(parent_item)
parent_id_for_children = next_id
next_id += 1
typer.echo(
    f"Added todo #{parent_item.id}: "
    f"{parent_item.title}"
)
@

Children are created recursively. Each child inherits the parent's
labels, deadline, assignee, and environment unless its own YAML block
overrides them.  We pass [[parent_who]] and [[parent_env]] explicitly
rather than reading
[[default_username]] again inside the function: the caller already
knows the resolved assignee (which may be a custom [[--who]] value),
so passing it through avoids a second lookup and keeps the function
independent of global state.  Passing the environment explicitly serves
the same purpose for context restoration: if the parent captured an
environment, children created in the editor inherit it unless they say
otherwise. When the parent has a numeric priority we still distribute
child priorities within the range computed by
[[compute_child_priority_range]] so that children sort between their
parent and the parent's next-lower sibling in flat view.  But when the
parent itself is unranked there is no meaningful numeric range yet, so
the children stay unranked too and wait for later [[reprioritize]]:

<<create children from parsed>>=
def create_children_from_parsed(
    parsed_children, parent_id,
    parent_labels, parent_deadline,
    priority_high, priority_low,
    parent_who=None,
    parent_env=None,
):
    """Recursively create TodoItems from parsed
    children.

    Priorities are distributed evenly in the range
    (priority_low, priority_high).  Each child
    inherits ``parent_who`` as its assignee unless
    the child's own YAML block specifies a
    ``who`` key.  Children inherit ``parent_env``
    unless they explicitly specify an ``env``
    block or request [[--here]]/[[--env]] on the
    command line before entering the editor.
    """
    nonlocal next_id, todos
    if (
        priority_high is not None
        and priority_low is not None
    ):
        priorities = distribute_priorities_in_range(
            len(parsed_children),
            priority_high, priority_low,
        )
    else:
        priorities = [None] * len(parsed_children)
    for i, parsed_child in enumerate(
        parsed_children
    ):
        prio = priorities[i]
        <<resolve child metadata>>
        <<create and append child item>>
        if parsed_child.children:
            <<nested child priority range>>
            create_children_from_parsed(
                parsed_child.children,
                child_id,
                child_labels,
                child_deadline,
                nested_high, nested_low,
                child_who,
                child_env,
            )
@

Each child overrides its metadata (labels, deadline, working
directory, assignee, environment) from the YAML block in the editor,
falling back to the parent's values when not specified.  The [[who]]
inheritance is especially important: without it, children typed
in the editor without an explicit [[who:]] key would be created
unassigned, even though the user intended the whole task tree to
belong to the same person.  Environment inheritance follows the same
logic: changing the directory should not silently replace the stored
environment, so [[wd]] and [[env]] are inherited independently.
<<resolve child metadata>>=
child_meta = parsed_child.metadata
child_labels = child_meta.get(
    "labels", list(parent_labels)
)
child_deadline = child_meta.get(
    "deadline", parent_deadline
)
child_who = child_meta.get("who", parent_who)
child_wd = canonicalize_wd(child_meta.get("wd"))
child_env = child_meta.get("env", parent_env)
@

We append the new item to [[todos]] immediately so that recursive
calls can see it as a parent when processing grandchildren.
<<create and append child item>>=
child = TodoItem(
    id=next_id,
    title=parsed_child.title,
    labels=child_labels,
    priority=prio,
    status="pending",
    created=now,
    deadline=child_deadline,
    estimated=(
        parse_hours(str(child_meta["estimate"]))
        if "estimate" in child_meta
        else None
    ),
    parent_id=parent_id,
    who=child_who,
    notes=parsed_child.notes,
    wd=child_wd,
    env=child_env,
    command=child_meta.get("command"),
)
todos.append(child)
child_id = next_id
next_id += 1
typer.echo(
    f"  Added sub-item #{child.id}: "
    f"{child.title}"
)
@

For nested children (grandchildren), the sub-range falls between the
current child's priority and the next child's priority. If this is the
last child, we use the range's lower bound instead.  Unranked children
propagate the unranked state downward by passing [[None]] for both ends
of the nested range:

<<nested child priority range>>=
if prio is None:
    nested_high = None
    nested_low = None
elif i + 1 < len(priorities):
    nested_high = prio
    nested_low = priorities[i + 1]
else:
    nested_high = prio
    nested_low = priority_low
@

The call site computes the parent's priority range from its sibling
context and passes the parent's [[who]] so that any child lacking
an explicit [[who:]] in its YAML block inherits the same assignee:

<<create children from parsed>>=
if parent_item.priority is None:
    prio_high = None
    prio_low = None
else:
    prio_high, prio_low = compute_child_priority_range(
        todos, parent_item
    )
create_children_from_parsed(
    parsed.children,
    parent_id_for_children,
    parent_item.labels,
    parent_item.deadline,
    prio_high, prio_low,
    parent_item.who,
    parent_item.env,
)
@

\subsection{The [[ls]] Command}

The list command shows ranked todos first, ordered by effective
priority, and then any unranked todos in deadline order. By default it
shows only top-level items (those without a parent), keeping the list
scannable without drowning the user in sub-tasks. The [[--all]] option
enables the full tree view: top-level items with their children
indented below. The [[--flat]] option shows a flat list in that same
display order instead of the indented tree.

We query tracked time by looking for entries with [[todo:<id>]] labels
in the track data, connecting the todo system to actual time spent.
Label filters are positional arguments, matching the [[add]] command's
convention ([[todo ls tilkry26 prep]] filters to items with either
label).

Three defaults on [[ls]] are worth making configurable so a user does
not have to retype the same flag on every invocation: the row cap
[[-n]], the output format, and the assignee filter.
We read each from [[typerconf]] once at module import via the shared
[[default]] helper (\cref{cli.utils.defaults}), giving Typer a
resolved value to display in [[--help]].
The [[--who]] fallback is [[default_username]] (that is, [[\$USER]]),
matching the pre-existing behaviour.
<<configuration>>=
TODO_LS_COUNT_CONFIG = "todo.ls.count"
TODO_LS_FORMAT_CONFIG = "todo.ls.format"
TODO_LS_WHO_CONFIG = "todo.ls.who"

DEFAULT_LS_COUNT = default(TODO_LS_COUNT_CONFIG, 10, int)
DEFAULT_LS_FORMAT = default(TODO_LS_FORMAT_CONFIG,
                            "table", str)
DEFAULT_LS_WHO = default(TODO_LS_WHO_CONFIG,
                         default_username, str)
@

