@cli.command(name="ls")
def ls(
    label_filter: Annotated[list[str] | None,
                            label_filter_arg] = None,
    include_done: Annotated[bool,
                            done_opt] = False,
    show_tree: Annotated[bool, ls_all_opt] = False,
    count: Annotated[int | None,
                     ls_count_opt] = DEFAULT_LS_COUNT,
    who_filter: Annotated[str | None,
                          ls_who_opt] = DEFAULT_LS_WHO,
    flat: Annotated[bool, ls_flat_opt] = False,
    output_format: Annotated[str,
                             ls_format_opt] = DEFAULT_LS_FORMAT,
    status_filter: Annotated[str | None,
                             ls_status_opt] = None,
    show_prio: Annotated[bool, ls_prio_opt] = False,
    output: Annotated[str | None,
                      ls_output_opt] = None,
):
    """List todo items in display order.

    Ranked items are shown first by effective priority; unranked
    items follow in deadline order. By default shows only top-level
    items assigned to the current user. Pass [[--all]] to see the
    full tree including subtasks, or [[-n N]] to cap the output at
    N items.

    [[--who]] defaults to [[\\$USER]]; pass an empty string
    ([[--who '']]) to show all assignees.

    Output format defaults to [[table]], which auto-detects the
    terminal: rich-formatted when stdout is a TTY, plain CSV
    otherwise (suitable for piping).
    """
    _, todos = load_todos()

    <<filter todos>>
    <<query tracked time>>
    <<restrict to top-level when not [[show_tree]]>>

    <<determine effective format>>

    if effective_format == "json":
        <<output json>>
    elif effective_format == "rich":
        <<output rich table>>
    else:
        <<output csv>>
@

The [[--status]] option enables exact status filtering, which the
agent workflow needs to query only pending tasks without fragile
[[awk]] filtering in shell scripts.  When [[--status]] is given, it
takes precedence over [[--done]] since the user has expressed a
more specific intent.

<<filter todos>>=
filtered = todos
if status_filter:
    filtered = [
        t for t in filtered
        if t.status == status_filter
    ]
elif not include_done:
    filtered = [
        t for t in filtered if t.status != "done"
    ]
if label_filter:
    filtered = [
        t for t in filtered
        if any(l in t.labels for l in label_filter)
    ]
if who_filter:
    filtered = [
        t for t in filtered
        if t.who and re.search(who_filter, t.who)
    ]
@

Let's verify that the [[--status]] filter correctly isolates items
by their current state:

