@

To show tracked time, we load track data and sum durations for
entries matching [[todo:<id>]] labels. This avoids duplicating the
track system's storage logic.

<<query tracked time>>=
tracked_times: dict[int, float] = {}
try:
    from nytid.cli.track import load_tracking_data

    entries = load_tracking_data()
    for entry in entries:
        for lbl in entry.labels:
            if lbl.startswith("todo:"):
                try:
                    tid = int(lbl.split(":")[1])
                    hours = (
                        entry.duration().total_seconds()
                        / 3600
                    )
                    tracked_times[tid] = (
                        tracked_times.get(tid, 0) + hours
                    )
                except (ValueError, IndexError):
                    pass
except ImportError:
    pass
@

Filters such as [[--who]] narrow [[filtered]] to a subset without
regard to hierarchy.  A subitem assigned to one person may have a
parent assigned to someone else; after filtering by [[--who]], the
parent is gone but the child remains.  Treating that child as
invisible because its [[parent_id is not None]] would silently hide
an item the filtered user is responsible for.

The right behaviour is to treat any item as a root when its parent
is absent from the filtered set---either because it is a true
top-level item, or because its parent was removed by a filter.  We
factor this into a helper so that both the non-tree restriction step
and the tree renderer share exactly the same logic, with no
duplication:

<<sub-item helpers>>=
def get_visible_roots(
    items: list[TodoItem],
) -> list[TodoItem]:
    """Return items whose parent is absent from items.

    An item is a visible root when it is a true top-level item
    (parent_id is None) or when its parent is not present in
    items---for example, because a --who filter removed it.  Pass a
    pre-filtered list, not the full todos.
    """
    ids = {t.id for t in items}
    return [
        t for t in items
        if t.parent_id is None
        or t.parent_id not in ids
    ]
@

When [[--all]] is not given, we restrict [[filtered]] to its
visible roots.  This keeps the list scannable by default: subitems
of a visible parent are subordinate detail the user can reveal on
demand with [[--all]].  Applying the restriction before the
format-selection branch keeps JSON, CSV, and rich table output
consistent.

<<restrict to top-level when not [[show_tree]]>>=
if not show_tree:
    filtered = get_visible_roots(filtered)
@

When [[--all]] is given the tree renderer already handles building
the top-level list itself, so we leave [[filtered]] untouched.

Let's verify the three new behaviours: the default top-level-only
view, the [[--all]] tree expansion, and the [[-n]] limit.

