When [[--format]] is [[table]] (the default) we auto-detect the
output context: a rich table when writing to a terminal, and
tab-separated CSV otherwise. This lets shell pipelines and
redirections receive machine-readable data without an explicit
flag, while interactive use stays human-readable. Forcing
[[--format rich]] or [[--format csv]] overrides the detection.
Specifying [[--output]] is treated as a non-interactive destination
and also selects CSV in auto-detect mode.

<<determine effective format>>=
if output_format == "json":
    effective_format = "json"
elif output_format == "rich":
    effective_format = "rich"
elif output_format == "csv":
    effective_format = "csv"
else:
    effective_format = (
        "csv"
        if (output or not sys.stdout.isatty())
        else "rich"
    )
@

JSON output uses the shared display order and respects the [[-n]] limit
just like the rich and CSV paths.  We sort here because JSON consumers
(scripts, agents) should receive items in the same priority order the
user would see interactively, and slicing with [[[:count]]] is a
no-op when [[count]] is [[None]].
Scripts that need the numeric score can request it with [[--prio]];
omitting it by default keeps the JSON payload small.

<<output json>>=
import json as json_mod

now = datetime.datetime.now()
sorted_filtered = sort_todos_for_display(
    filtered, now
)[:count]
output = []
for t in sorted_filtered:
    d = t.to_dict()
    if show_prio:
        d["effective_priority"] = effective_priority(
            t, now
        )
    d["tracked_hours"] = tracked_times.get(t.id, 0)
    output.append(d)
print(json_mod.dumps(output, indent=2))
@

For rich table output we use [[rich.table.Table]] so the
terminal gets nicely aligned, coloured columns. The tree layout
is preserved: children are indented with a \enquote{└─} prefix
in the Title column, and a dimmed progress summary follows each
parent that has children.

That progress summary must also land in the Title column when the
optional priority column is hidden. A fixed [[table.add_row("", "",
progress)]] only works when [[--prio]] is enabled; otherwise the
summary shifts into the [[Who]] column. We therefore compute the
leading empty cells from [[show_prio]] so the summary stays aligned
with the task title in both layouts. We use a single [[Console]] to
respect the terminal width automatically.

Effective priority is still the primary sort key for ranked items but is
not surfaced
by default in any output format. The numeric score is an
internal detail: in table output it clutters the view, and in
CSV/JSON it adds a field that most scripts do not need.
Passing [[--prio]] opts in across all three formats, which is
useful when debugging why an item ranked unexpectedly or when
writing a script that needs a comparable score.  Unranked items leave
that field blank (or [[null]] in JSON), making the absence of a numeric
priority visible instead of pretending it is zero.

<<output rich table>>=
