Subitems inherit their parent's labels, so a child todo
typically shares labels like course codes with its parent.
The tracking session stores each label only once (dict-based),
so stopping a shared label in one todo silently removes it
from every other active todo that depends on it.

Three code paths need to stop tracking---[[done]]/[[rm]],
the post-subprocess finalizer, and the [[stop]] command---so
we factor the logic into a function rather than a reusable
chunk.  A function makes the dependencies explicit through
parameters: a missing argument is caught at call time, whereas
a chunk that implicitly references [[todo_id]] or [[todos]]
would only fail at runtime if a prerequisite chunk were
omitted.

The function collects labels that are still needed by other
todos on the active stack and excludes them from the stop
list, preventing a child from accidentally removing labels
shared with its parent.  These are the 
\enquote{protected} labels: labels that belong to the todo being
stopped, but also to some other todo that remains active.  For example,
if a parent and child both carry [[DD1310]], completing the child should
stop [[todo:child]] but leave [[DD1310]] running for the parent.

Protection only considers items belonging to the \emph{same} worker.
Each worker has an independent tracking session, so another worker's
active todo cannot keep your labels alive---and should not prevent them
from being stopped.  Without this restriction, a parent task owned by
worker~A would shield labels from being stopped for worker~B, leaving
B's tracking session with dangling open entries.

The caller is responsible for managing the active-todo stack; this
function only reads it to compute that protection set.  Once it has
decided which labels ought to stop, it delegates the actual tracking
mutation to the public helper in [[cli.track]].  This is the key
architectural boundary: [[cli.todo]] owns todo state and stack policy,
while [[cli.track]] owns all persistence and mutation of tracking data.
With that split, [[todo start]], [[todo stop]], and [[todo done]] become
wrappers around track semantics rather than a second implementation of
them.

<<helpers>>=
def stop_todo_tracking(todo_id, item, todos):
    """Stop tracking labels for a todo item.

    Protects labels still needed by other active
    todos on the stack.
    """
    try:
        from nytid.cli.track import (
            stop_tracking_labels_if_active,
        )

        worker = item.who or default_username
        todo_label = f"todo:{todo_id}"
        stack = normalize_active_stack(
            todos, load_active_stack_raw()
        )
        protected = set()
        for sid in stack:
            if sid == todo_id:
                continue
            stacked = next(
                (t for t in todos if t.id == sid),
                None,
            )
            if stacked and (
                stacked.who or default_username
            ) == worker:
                protected.update(stacked.labels)

        labels_to_stop = [todo_label] + [
            label for label in item.labels
            if label not in protected
        ]
        _, completed_entries, active_labels = (
            stop_tracking_labels_if_active(
                who=worker,
                labels=labels_to_stop,
                end_time=datetime.datetime.now(),
            )
        )
        if not completed_entries:
            return
        typer.echo(
            "  Stopped tracking: "
            f"{', '.join(active_labels)}"
        )
    except ImportError:
        pass
@

