\subsubsection{Auto-stopping Descendants}

When a parent is stopped, any active descendants should be stopped as
well.  A child left running while its parent is off the stack would be an
orphan---[[todo status]] would show a broken hierarchy, and the child's
labels would be tracked without the parent's context.

The inverse of [[ensure_ancestors_active]]: we walk \emph{down} the tree,
depth-first, collecting every active descendant.  Depth-first order means
a grandchild appears before its parent, matching the natural LIFO unwind.

Both stopping and force-completing need the same traversal, so we start
with a pure-read helper that returns the list of active descendant IDs
without mutating anything.

<<helpers>>=
def get_active_descendant_ids(
    todo_id, todos, who=None
):
    """Return IDs of active descendants for one worker.

    Pure read---no mutations.  Depth-first order
    (deepest descendants first).  When ``who`` is
    given, only descendants active for that worker
    are returned.
    """
    stack = load_active_stack()
    if who is not None:
        stack = filter_ids_by_worker(
            todos, stack, who
        )
    found = []

    def collect(parent_id):
        children = get_children(todos, parent_id)
        for child in children:
            collect(child.id)
            if child.id in stack:
                found.append(child.id)

    collect(todo_id)
    return found
@

[[stop_active_descendants]] builds on that traversal: for each active
descendant it stops tracking, then removes all of them from the stack
in a single mutation.  The optional [[who]] filter matters because the
stack is global across workers while tracking sessions are not.

<<helpers>>=
def stop_active_descendants(
    todo_id, todos, who=None
):
    """Stop tracking and deactivate descendants.

    Recursively walks children of ``todo_id``,
    stopping tracking and removing each active
    descendant from the stack.  Returns the list of
    IDs that were deactivated.  When ``who`` is
    given, only that worker's descendants are
    touched.
    """
    stopped_ids = get_active_descendant_ids(
        todo_id, todos, who=who
    )

    if not stopped_ids:
        return []

    by_id = {t.id: t for t in todos}
    for cid in stopped_ids:
        child_item = by_id.get(cid)
        if child_item is not None:
            stop_todo_tracking(cid, child_item, todos)
            typer.echo(
                f"  Auto-stopped child: "
                f"#{cid} {child_item.title}"
            )

    def remove_from_stack(next_id, todos, stack):
        stack = [
            sid for sid in stack
            if sid not in stopped_ids
        ]
        return next_id, todos, stack

    mutate_todo_state(remove_from_stack)
    return stopped_ids
@

Callers rarely want just one piece of that protocol.  The common
high-level operation is
\enquote{stop this todo the same way [[todo stop]] would}:
remove the target from the stack, stop its own
tracking labels, then unwind any active descendants beneath it.

We package that policy into [[stop_todo_hierarchy]] so manual
[[todo stop]], blocked subprocess cleanup, and detached tmux finalization
all share one implementation.  The helper stops at the hierarchy
boundary; callers remain free to apply their own post-stop status policy
such as prompting for completion or resetting unfinished work to
[[pending]].

<<helpers>>=
def stop_todo_hierarchy(todo_id, who=None):
    """Stop a todo and all active descendants.

    Reuses the same hierarchy-unwinding order as
    ``todo stop`` and returns the refreshed todo
    state after descendants have been deactivated.
    """
    resolved_id, item, _, todos, _ = stop_todo_state(
        todo_id, who=who
    )
    resolved_who = who
    if resolved_who is None and item is not None:
        resolved_who = item.who or default_username
    stop_todo_tracking(resolved_id, item, todos)
    stopped_ids = stop_active_descendants(
        resolved_id, todos, who=resolved_who
    )
    next_id, todos, stack = load_todo_state()
    by_id = {t.id: t for t in todos}
    descendants = [
        by_id[cid]
        for cid in stopped_ids
        if cid in by_id
    ]
    return (
        resolved_id,
        by_id.get(resolved_id),
        next_id,
        todos,
        stack,
        descendants,
    )
@

The [[done]] command also needs the traversal, but its response differs:
rather than stopping tracking, it marks each descendant as done.
[[force_complete_descendants]] handles the [[--force]] path.

<<helpers>>=
def force_complete_descendants(
    todo_id, todos, who=None
):
    """Mark active descendants as done.

    For each active descendant (depth-first): stop
    tracking, mark done, and remove from the stack.
    The [[done --force]] path uses this helper to keep
    the whole subtree consistent, so active descendants
    are completed regardless of worker.
    """
    desc_ids = get_active_descendant_ids(
        todo_id, todos
    )
    if not desc_ids:
        return

    by_id = {t.id: t for t in todos}
    for cid in desc_ids:
        child_item = by_id.get(cid)
        if child_item is not None:
            stop_todo_tracking(
                cid, child_item, todos
            )

    def mark_done(next_id, todos, stack):
        for cid in desc_ids:
            child = next(
                (t for t in todos if t.id == cid),
                None,
            )
            if child and child.status != "done":
                child.status = "done"
                typer.echo(
                    f"  Force-completed: "
                    f"#{child.id} {child.title}"
                )
        stack = [
            sid for sid in stack
            if sid not in desc_ids
        ]
        return next_id, todos, stack

    mutate_todo_state(mark_done)
@

The guard chunk checks for active descendants before completing.  Without
[[--force]], it lists the offending children and exits.  With [[--force]],
it completes them recursively for any worker before proceeding with the
parent.  That keeps the subtree invariant intact: a completed parent must
not retain an active descendant on someone else's stack.

The guard must resolve the target ID first so it knows which item to
check.  We use [[resolve_done_target]] for that, which keeps the
explicit-ID ownership rule aligned with the later locked completion.

<<guard active descendants>>=
_, preflight_todos = load_todos()
resolved_id, _ = resolve_done_target(
    todo_id, preflight_todos, who=who
)
desc_ids = get_active_descendant_ids(
    resolved_id, preflight_todos
)
if desc_ids and not force:
    by_id = {t.id: t for t in preflight_todos}
    typer.echo(
        f"Error: todo #{resolved_id} has active "
        f"descendants:",
        err=True,
    )
    for cid in desc_ids:
        child = by_id.get(cid)
        if child:
            typer.echo(
                f"  #{child.id} {child.title}",
                err=True,
            )
    typer.echo(
        "Use --force to mark all descendants "
        "as done.",
        err=True,
    )
    raise typer.Exit(1)
if desc_ids and force:
    force_complete_descendants(
        resolved_id, preflight_todos
    )
