Starting a todo delegates to the track system. We start tracking with
the todo's labels plus a special [[todo:<id>]] label, and set the
todo's status to \enquote{in-progress}. The track worker is the todo's
assigned worker, defaulting to \enquote{me}.

The ordering now matters more than before.  We first update the
authoritative active stack under the todo lock, then start the matching
track labels.  This means that auto-parenting, [[todo status]], and
subsequent [[todo next]] decisions immediately see the new active
hierarchy even if the launched subprocess has not yet done anything.

The key enhancement: if the todo has a [[wd]], [[start]] automatically
spawns a subprocess---the stored [[command]], a [[--command]] override, or
[[$SHELL]]. This combines the patterns from launch-enabled
[[track start]] (tracking bookends around a subprocess) and
[[courses data]] shell (PS1 modification and [[wd]] control).
When the subprocess exits, tracking stops and blocking launches ask
whether the todo should be marked done.

Without a [[wd]], the command behaves as before: it starts tracking
without spawning anything.

As with [[view]] and friends, omitting the ID means \enquote{start the
current active todo}.  In tmux that follows the pane or window labels;
an untracked tmux pane/window has no implicit active todo, while
outside tmux it falls back to the worker's active-stack top.  This is
useful when tracking stopped but the todo itself remains the current
focus.

<<start command>>=
@cli.command()
def start(
    todo_id: Annotated[int | None,
                       todo_id_arg] = None,
    <<start command options>>
):
    """Start tracking time for a todo item.

    If no ID given, starts the current active task.

    If the todo has a working directory, spawns a
    shell or command in that directory with tracking.
    """
    todo_id, item, next_id, todos, stack = activate_todo_state(
        todo_id, who=default_username
    )

    <<resolve tmux context sync policy>>
    <<auto-activate ancestors>>
    <<start tracking via track module>>

    typer.echo(
        f"Started: #{todo_id} {item.title}"
    )

    <<spawn subprocess if wd or run>>
@

Detached tmux cleanup happens after the pane process exits, so it cannot
reuse the in-memory todo item from the original [[start]] call.  We
therefore provide a hidden helper command that reloads the todo,
stops it through the same hierarchy-unwinding helper as manual
[[todo stop]], and applies the post-run policy in a fresh process.

That helper must be robust against exactly the kinds of changes that may
happen during a long-running task.  The working directory might have been
renamed or deleted before the pane exits, so cleanup must not depend on
[[cd]] into [[wd]].  Likewise, [[nytid]] may be running inside a Poetry
environment or another non-system interpreter, so the detached helper
must reuse [[sys.executable]] rather than assuming [[python3]] points at
the correct environment.

<<helpers>>=
def finalize_detached_todo(
    todo_id, exit_code=1, exit_code_file=None
):
    """Finish a non-blocking tmux-backed todo run."""
    if exit_code_file is not None:
        exit_code = read_detached_exit_code(
            exit_code_file
        )
    (
        todo_id,
        item,
        next_id,
        todos,
        stack,
        descendants,
    ) = stop_todo_hierarchy(
        todo_id
    )
    if item is None:
        return

    result = type(
        "DetachedResult", (),
        {
            "returncode": exit_code,
            "stdout": None,
        },
    )()

    if item.status != "done":
        item.status = "pending"
    for child in descendants:
        if child.status != "done":
            child.status = "pending"

    save_todos(next_id, todos)


def run_todo_tmux_command(*args, **kwargs):
    """Delegate tmux launches to the track module helper."""
    from nytid.cli.track import run_tmux_command
    return run_tmux_command(*args, **kwargs)


def read_detached_exit_code(exit_code_file):
    """Read a tmux-recorded exit code for detached todo cleanup."""
    try:
        from nytid.cli.track import read_tmux_exit_status
        return read_tmux_exit_status(exit_code_file)
    except ImportError:
        return 1


def build_detached_todo_finalize_command(
    todo_id, proc_wd, exit_code_file
):
    """Return shell command to finalize a detached todo run."""
    pythonpath = os.path.abspath(
        os.path.join(
            os.path.dirname(__file__), "..", "..", ".."
        )
    )
    return (
        f"PYTHONPATH={shlex.quote(pythonpath)} "
        f"{shlex.quote(sys.executable)} "
        "-c 'from nytid.cli.todo import cli; cli()' "
        f"_finalize-detached {todo_id} "
        f"--exit-code-file {shlex.quote(exit_code_file)}"
        f"; rm -f {shlex.quote(exit_code_file)}"
    )
@

<<argument and option definitions>>=
finalize_id_arg = typer.Argument(
    help="Todo ID to finalize")
finalize_exit_arg = typer.Argument(
    help="Exit code from the process")
finalize_file_opt = typer.Option(
    "--exit-code-file",
    help="File containing the exit code")
@

<<detached finalize command>>=
@cli.command(name="_finalize-detached", hidden=True)
def finalize_detached_cmd(
    todo_id: Annotated[int, finalize_id_arg],
    exit_code: Annotated[int,
                         finalize_exit_arg] = 1,
    exit_code_file: Annotated[str | None,
                              finalize_file_opt] = None,
):
    """Finalize a detached tmux-backed todo run."""
    finalize_detached_todo(
        todo_id, exit_code, exit_code_file
    )
