@

For cron and agent workflows, we need a non-interactive mode that
skips the [[typer.confirm]] prompt after subprocess exit.  In headless
mode, the logic is: if the subprocess (e.g.\ [[claude]]) already called
[[todo done]] during its run, the task is done; otherwise we reset to
pending so the next invocation can retry.

\paragraph{Full lifecycle in headless mode}
\label{sec:headless-lifecycle}
When [[--headless]] is combined with [[--timeout]], the [[start]]
command manages the full lifecycle internally: capturing output,
posting it as a note, handling timeout, and reassigning timed-out
tasks.  This eliminates the race condition where an external
shell script queries for the active task after the subprocess has
already reset the status (see \cref{sec:agent-automation}).

<<start command options>>=
headless: Annotated[bool, headless_opt] = False,
@

The [[--timeout]] and [[--reassign-to]] options are orthogonal to
[[--headless]]: timeout specifies when to kill a runaway subprocess
(using GNU [[timeout]] format like [[50m]] or [[1.5h]]), and
[[--reassign-to]] specifies who receives timed-out or failed tasks.
Keeping them separate makes each parameter's purpose clear and
allows independent configuration.

<<start command options>>=
timeout: Annotated[str | None,
                   timeout_opt] = None,
reassign_to: Annotated[str | None,
                       reassign_opt] = default_username,
@

Tmux gives us a middle ground between blocking the current terminal and
running fully headless.  [[--pane]] keeps the task visible beside the
current shell, while [[--window]] moves it to another tmux window in the
same session.  Because both modes rely on tmux owning the terminal, they
require [[TMUX]] to be set and cannot be combined with [[--headless]].
By default tmux launches detach immediately so the caller can keep using
other panes while the task remains tracked.  [[--block]] switches back to
the interactive completion workflow: when the pane command exits,
tracking stops and the user decides whether the task is done. Detached
tmux runs still stop tracking automatically and reset the todo to
pending unless it was already marked done from inside the pane.

<<start command options>>=
pane: Annotated[bool, pane_opt] = False,
window: Annotated[bool, window_opt] = False,
block: Annotated[bool | None,
                 block_opt] = None,
@

When running in a tmux pane, tracking can automatically suspend
when the pane loses focus and resume when it regains focus.  The
[[--auto-suspend]]/[[--no-auto-suspend]] flag overrides the
per-worker and global config defaults; see the [[track]] module
(\cref{track:auto-suspend}) for the resolution order.

<<start command options>>=
auto_suspend: Annotated[
    bool | None, auto_suspend_opt
] = None,
@

We reject impossible combinations before building the subprocess command.
This keeps the later chunks focused on one execution mode at a time and
produces clear CLI errors for mutually exclusive options.

<<validate tmux options>>=
try:
    from nytid.cli.track import validate_tmux_options
    validate_tmux_options(pane, window)
except ImportError:
    if pane and window:
        typer.echo(
            "Error: --pane and --window are mutually exclusive",
            err=True,
        )
        raise typer.Exit(1)
    if (pane or window) and not os.environ.get("TMUX"):
        typer.echo(
            "Error: --pane/--window require an active tmux session",
            err=True,
        )
        raise typer.Exit(1)
except ValueError as exc:
    typer.echo(str(exc), err=True)
    raise typer.Exit(1)
if (pane or window) and headless:
    typer.echo(
        "Error: --pane/--window cannot be used with --headless",
        err=True,
    )
    raise typer.Exit(1)
if block is None:
    block = not (pane or window)
if block and not (pane or window):
    pass
if not block and not (pane or window):
    typer.echo(
        "Error: --no-block requires --pane or --window",
        err=True,
    )
    raise typer.Exit(1)
@

We import and use the track module's start/stop helpers directly rather
than shelling out to the CLI. This keeps todo launches aligned with the
same on-disk locking and persistence semantics as the track commands.

Before we start tracking the explicitly requested todo, we ensure that
all its ancestors are already active and tracked.  This way, starting
a sub-item \enquote{just works} without requiring the user to manually
start each ancestor first.

The same tmux-context rule applies to both ancestor and main-item
tracking.  Detached tmux launches should not first publish labels into
the source shell's pane or window; they should wait for the tmux launch
helper to declare the new pane or window as tracked.

<<resolve tmux context sync policy>>=
update_tmux_context = not (pane or window)
@

<<auto-activate ancestors>>=
ensure_ancestors_active(
    item,
    todos,
    stack,
    update_tmux_context=update_tmux_context,
)
@

<<start tracking via track module>>=
try:
    from nytid.cli.track import (
        start_tracking_labels,
    )

    worker = item.who or default_username

    track_labels = list(item.labels) + [
        f"todo:{todo_id}"
    ]
    started, _, _ = start_tracking_labels(
        track_labels,
        start_time=datetime.datetime.now(),
        who=worker,
        update_tmux_context=update_tmux_context,
    )

    if started:
        typer.echo(
            f"  Tracking: {', '.join(sorted(started))}"
        )
        if worker != "me":
            typer.echo(f"  Worker: {worker}")
except ImportError:
    typer.echo(
        "Warning: track module not available, "
        "time tracking disabled",
        err=True,
    )
@

\subsubsection{Spawning a Subprocess}

When the todo has a [[wd]], when [[--command]] is given, or when the user
explicitly requests [[--pane]]/[[--window]], we spawn a subprocess with
the stored environment restored. The environment restoration starts
from the stored [[env]] (if available) and overlays terminal-related
variables ([[TERM]], [[DISPLAY]], [[SSH_*]]) from the current
environment to ensure the terminal works correctly.

The PS1 prefix should only be injected when we are actually launching an
interactive shell.  Arbitrary commands such as [[claude]], [[opencode]],
[[echo]], or [[false]] must run exactly as resolved; otherwise the shared
shell helper would incorrectly replace the requested command with the
user's login shell.

<<spawn subprocess if wd or run>>=
if item.wd or run or pane or window:
    <<validate tmux options>>
    <<prepare subprocess environment>>
    <<determine command to run>>
    <<resolve todo auto-suspend>>
    if pane or window:
        <<run in tmux>>
        if block:
            <<handle subprocess exit>>
    else:
        <<adjust shell command for prompt>>
        <<run subprocess>>
        <<handle subprocess exit>>
@

Todo launches now follow the same context-building path as track launches.
We compute the textual todo context once, apply it to [[PS1]], and then reuse
the same value for tmux window names.  That keeps direct shells and [[-W]]
windows visually consistent.

<<prepare subprocess environment>>=
from nytid.cli.track import (
    apply_context_prompt,
    build_context_name,
)

proc_env = os.environ.copy()
if item.env:
    proc_env = dict(item.env)
    # Overlay terminal variables from current env
    for key in os.environ:
        if key in (
            "TERM", "DISPLAY", "COLORTERM",
            "TERM_PROGRAM",
        ) or key.startswith("SSH_"):
            proc_env[key] = os.environ[key]
todo_context = build_context_name(
    "todo", [str(todo_id)]
)
apply_context_prompt(todo_context, proc_env)
proc_wd = item.wd or os.getcwd()
prompt_file = None
prompt_dir = None
@

The command resolution follows a priority chain: [[--command]] overrides
the stored [[command]], which overrides [[$SHELL]].  We parse command
strings with [[shlex.split]] so quoted arguments survive intact.
When the resolved launcher is [[claude]] or [[opencode]] and the user
specified only the bare command, we append the todo's notes or
description as a prompt argument.  If the user already supplied flags
such as [[-p]], we respect that command line exactly.

This gives two distinct workflows.  Storing plain [[claude]] means the
todo text itself is the prompt source, so later edits to notes or
description automatically change what the agent sees.  Storing
[[claude -p "..."]], by contrast, freezes the prompt in the command,
which is useful when the launcher instruction should stay stable even if
the todo text evolves.

<<determine command to run>>=
from nytid.cli.track import build_plain_shell_command

cmd_str = run or item.command
if cmd_str:
    prompt_text = item.notes or item.description
    cmd = shlex.split(cmd_str)
    if not cmd:
        cmd = build_plain_shell_command(proc_env)
    elif cmd[0] in ("claude", "opencode"):
        has_prompt = any(
            part in ("-p", "--prompt")
            for part in cmd[1:]
        )
        if prompt_text and not has_prompt:
            cmd = cmd + [prompt_text]
else:
    cmd = build_plain_shell_command(proc_env)
@

Tmux gives the subprocess its own terminal while keeping the launch
under our control.  We reuse the [[track]] module's helper so both
commands share the same pane startup handshake, exit-status recording,
and blocking semantics.  For detached todo runs we swap the blocking
wait channel for a follow-up shell command that re-enters [[todo]] and
applies the pending/done cleanup policy after the pane process exits.
Blocked launches now rejoin the same post-exit path as direct
subprocesses: once tmux reports that the pane session is over, we still
reload the todo state, stop tracking, and ask whether the item should be
marked done.

Auto-suspend resolution follows the same pattern as [[track start]]:
the CLI flag overrides config, and we warn about [[focus-events]] at
launch time.  We recompute [[worker]] and [[track_labels]] here
rather than relying on the earlier tracking block, which may have
been skipped if the [[track]] module was unavailable.

<<resolve todo auto-suspend>>=
worker = item.who or default_username
track_labels = list(item.labels) + [
    f"todo:{todo_id}"
]
use_auto_suspend = should_auto_suspend(
    worker, auto_suspend,
)
if use_auto_suspend and (pane or window):
    warn_if_focus_events_off()
focus_labels_for_tmux = (
    track_labels if use_auto_suspend else None
)
focus_who_for_tmux = (
    worker if use_auto_suspend else None
)
focus_window_for_tmux = bool(
    window and use_auto_suspend
)
@

The [[focus_window_for_tmux]] flag mirrors the computation in
[[track start]]'s [[<<run launched process>>]] chunk.  Without it,
[[run_tmux_command]] treats a [[--window]] launch as a plain pane
launch for auto-suspend purposes: pane-focus hooks then suspend
tracking the moment the user alt-tabs away, instead of the deferred
window-event buffering that keeps a tracked window \enquote{sticky}
across window switches.  Passing it makes [[todo ... -W]] register
the new window as a tracked window in exactly the same way as
[[track start -W]].

A more defensive API would have [[run_tmux_command]] derive
[[focus_window]] internally from [[window and focus_labels is not None]],
so that no caller could ever forget to opt in.  We keep it as an
explicit parameter for now---the [[track]] module already exposes
[[focus_window]] as a public knob and changing its semantics would
ripple through the tracked-window state machine---but the
duplicated computation here and in [[track]]'s
[[<<run launched process>>]] is a smell worth revisiting if a
third call site ever appears.

<<run in tmux>>=
try:
    exit_code_file = None
    if block:
        result = type(
            "TmuxResult", (),
            {
                "returncode": run_todo_tmux_command(
                    cmd,
                    cwd=proc_wd,
                    env=proc_env,
                    window=window,
                    window_name=(
                        todo_context
                        if window else None
                    ),
                    focus_labels=focus_labels_for_tmux,
                    focus_who=focus_who_for_tmux,
                    focus_window=focus_window_for_tmux,
                ),
                "stdout": None,
            },
        )()
    else:
        exit_fd, exit_code_file = tempfile.mkstemp(
            prefix="nytid-todo-",
            suffix=".status",
        )
        os.close(exit_fd)
        finalize_cmd = build_detached_todo_finalize_command(
            todo_id, proc_wd, exit_code_file
        )
        run_todo_tmux_command(
            cmd,
            cwd=proc_wd,
            env=proc_env,
            window=window,
            window_name=(
                todo_context
                if window else None
            ),
            block=False,
            exit_status_file=exit_code_file,
            on_exit_shell=finalize_cmd,
            focus_labels=focus_labels_for_tmux,
            focus_who=focus_who_for_tmux,
            focus_window=focus_window_for_tmux,
        )
        result = None
except subprocess.CalledProcessError as exc:
    typer.echo(
        f"tmux failed with exit code {exc.returncode}",
        err=True,
    )
    if exit_code_file is not None:
        try:
            os.unlink(exit_code_file)
        except OSError:
            pass
    raise typer.Exit(1)
except FileNotFoundError:
    typer.echo("tmux not found", err=True)
    if exit_code_file is not None:
        try:
            os.unlink(exit_code_file)
        except OSError:
            pass
    raise typer.Exit(1)
@

Now let's verify tmux integration starts the subprocess in tmux instead
of attaching it to the current terminal:

<<test functions>>=
def test_start_pane_without_command_uses_plain_tmux_shell(
    temp_todo_dir,
):
    """A tmux todo shell launch reuses the shared plain shell helper."""
    save_todos(2, [
        TodoItem(
            id=1, title="Review PR",
            created="2026-02-20T10:00:00",
            wd="/tmp/project",
        ),
    ])
    with patch.dict(
        os.environ,
        {"TMUX": "session", "SHELL": "/bin/bash"},
        clear=True,
    ):
        with patch(
            "nytid.cli.todo.run_todo_tmux_command",
            return_value=0,
        ) as mock_run:
            result = runner.invoke(
                cli, ["start", "1", "--pane"]
            )
    assert result.exit_code == 0
    mock_run.assert_called_once()
    call_kwargs = mock_run.call_args.kwargs
    assert mock_run.call_args.args == (["/bin/bash"],)
    assert call_kwargs["cwd"] == "/tmp/project"
    assert call_kwargs["env"] == {
        "PS1": "todo:1 \\w\\n$ ",
        "SHELL": "/bin/bash",
        "TMUX": "session",
    }
    assert call_kwargs["window"] is False
    assert call_kwargs["window_name"] is None
    assert call_kwargs["block"] is False
    assert "_finalize-detached 1 --exit-code-file" in call_kwargs["on_exit_shell"]


