@

The subprocess must behave differently depending on context.
Interactive users need a live terminal connection (pass-through
stdin/stdout/stderr), while headless agents have no terminal at
all---trying to read from a closed stdin would hang.  Redirecting
to [[subprocess.DEVNULL]] and [[subprocess.PIPE]] solves both
problems: no hang risk, and we capture output for the note.

Python's [[subprocess.run]] accepts a [[timeout]] parameter
natively, so we can retire the external [[timeout]] command
that wrapped the shell invocation
(see \cref{sec:agent-automation}).

As with all interactive child-process spawns, we ignore
\textsc{sigint} in the parent while the child is running.
[[subprocess.run]] resets [[SIG_IGN]] signals to [[SIG_DFL]] in
the child before [[exec]] (via [[restore_signals=True]]), so
Ctrl+C still reaches the child normally.  The parent resumes after
the child exits and can record the outcome.  We restore the
original handler at the start of the [[finally]] clause, before
the prompt-file cleanup, so the handler is reinstated even when
the cleanup itself fails.

<<run subprocess>>=
result = None
old_sigint = signal.signal(
    signal.SIGINT, signal.SIG_IGN
)
try:
    typer.echo(
        f"  Spawning in {proc_wd}: "
        f"{' '.join(cmd)}"
    )
    timeout_secs = (
        parse_timeout(timeout)
        if timeout else None
    )
    if headless:
        result = subprocess.run(
            cmd,
            cwd=proc_wd,
            env=proc_env,
            stdin=subprocess.DEVNULL,
            stdout=subprocess.PIPE,
            stderr=subprocess.STDOUT,
            text=True,
            timeout=timeout_secs,
        )
    else:
        result = subprocess.run(
            cmd,
            cwd=proc_wd,
            env=proc_env,
            stdin=sys.stdin,
            stdout=sys.stdout,
            stderr=sys.stderr,
            timeout=timeout_secs,
        )
except subprocess.TimeoutExpired as exc:
    <<handle subprocess timeout>>
except FileNotFoundError:
    typer.echo(
        f"Command not found: {cmd[0]}",
        err=True,
    )
finally:
    signal.signal(signal.SIGINT, old_sigint)
    <<cleanup temp prompt files>>
@

When a [[--timeout]] fires, [[subprocess.TimeoutExpired]] carries
any partial output captured before the kill signal.  We post that
partial output as a note (so the teacher sees what the agent
managed to do), reassign the task to [[--reassign-to]] (defaulting
to [[$USER]]), and reset to pending.  Setting [[result = None]]
signals to the exit handler that timeout was already handled.

<<handle subprocess timeout>>=
partial = (
    exc.stdout if exc.stdout else ""
)
# Reload and post timeout note
next_id, todos = load_todos()
item = next(
    (t for t in todos if t.id == todo_id),
    None,
)
if item is not None:
    note = (
        f"**Timed out** after {timeout}\n\n"
    )
    if partial.strip():
        note += (
            f"Partial output:\n"
            f"```\n{partial.strip()}\n```"
        )
    append_note_to_item(
        item, note, next_id, todos
    )
    if reassign_to:
        item.who = reassign_to
    item.status = "pending"
    save_todos(next_id, todos)
typer.echo(
    f"  Timed out after {timeout}",
    err=True,
)
@

After the subprocess exits, we stop the todo through the same shared
hierarchy helper used by manual [[todo stop]] and detached tmux cleanup,
then prompt the user about completion status.  In headless mode we skip
the prompt: if the subprocess already marked the todo done (via
[[todo done]]), we respect that; otherwise we reset the todo and any
auto-stopped descendants to pending for retry.

When headless mode captured output (via [[subprocess.PIPE]]),
we post it as a note before updating the status.  This ensures
the teacher can review what the agent did, even if the task
failed or was reset.

<<handle subprocess exit>>=
(
    todo_id,
    item,
    next_id,
    todos,
    stack,
    descendants,
) = stop_todo_hierarchy(
    todo_id
)
if item is None:
    return
<<post headless output as note>>

if item.status == "done":
    pass
elif headless:
    <<handle headless exit status>>
elif typer.confirm(
    f"Mark todo #{todo_id} as done?"
):
    item.status = "done"
else:
    item.status = "pending"

for child in descendants:
    if child.status != "done":
        child.status = "pending"

save_todos(next_id, todos)
if item.status == "done":
    auto_complete_parent(item, todos)
@

The exit code and captured output form a diagnostic record---the
teacher can review what the agent did without needing to check
system logs or reproduce the run.

<<post headless output as note>>=
if headless and result is not None:
    output = getattr(result, "stdout", None)
    code = result.returncode
    if output and output.strip():
        note = (
            f"Exit code: {code}\n\n"
            f"```\n{output.strip()}\n```"
        )
    else:
        note = f"Exit code: {code} (no output)"
    append_note_to_item(
        item, note, next_id, todos
    )
@

In headless mode, a non-zero exit code indicates failure.
If [[--reassign-to]] is set, we hand the task back to a human
so they can investigate.  A zero exit
code where the subprocess did not mark the task done means the
agent finished without completing the task---we reset to
pending for the next retry.

<<handle headless exit status>>=
if (
    result is not None
    and result.returncode != 0
    and reassign_to
):
    item.who = reassign_to
item.status = "pending"
