\subsection{The [[stop]] Command}

Stopping can target a specific todo by ID, or if no ID is given, find
whichever todo is currently being tracked and stop it.

Manual stopping uses the same hierarchy helper as subprocess and tmux
exit handling.  That keeps the high-level rule uniform across all three
paths: stopping a parent also unwinds any active descendants before the
caller decides what status changes, if any, should follow.

<<stop command>>=
@cli.command()
def stop(
    todo_id: Annotated[int | None,
                       todo_id_arg] = None,
):
    """Stop tracking time for a todo item.

    If no ID given, stops the currently tracked todo.
    Also stops any active descendants.
    """
    (
        todo_id,
        item,
        next_id,
        todos,
        stack,
        descendants,
    ) = stop_todo_hierarchy(
        todo_id, who=default_username
    )
    typer.echo(f"Stopped: #{todo_id} {item.title}")
