The metadata and placement options mirror [[todo add]] where they make
sense for batch imports.  [[--parent]] places imported items explicitly,
while [[--top-level]] suppresses the new auto-parenting behaviour.  When
neither is given, we reuse the currently tracked todo as the parent so a
teacher can start a broad task such as
\enquote{prepare course backlog} and import discovered GitHub work under
it naturally.

<<import metadata options>>=
deadline: Annotated[str | None,
                    deadline_opt] = None,
estimate: Annotated[str | None,
                    estimate_opt] = None,
description: Annotated[str | None,
                       description_opt] = "",
wd_path: Annotated[str | None, wd_opt] = None,
capture_env: Annotated[bool, env_opt] = False,
here: Annotated[bool, here_opt] = False,
run_command: Annotated[str | None,
                       command_opt] = None,
parent: Annotated[int | None,
                  parent_opt] = None,
top_level: Annotated[bool, top_level_opt] = False,
@

Parent inheritance works slightly differently for imports than for plain
[[todo add]].  Imported items always retain their repository label
because that is how users later find all issues from one project, but a
parent can still contribute its own labels and deadline when the user
does not specify overrides.  This lets a parent like [[DD1310]] provide
course context while [[owner/repo]] still marks the GitHub source.

If tmux is active but the current pane/window has no tracked todo,
imports stay top-level rather than inheriting another window's branch.

<<resolve import parent and inherited metadata>>=
resolved_parent = parent
parent_item = None
if parent is None and not top_level:
    active = get_current_context_todo(todos)
    if active is not None:
        resolved_parent = active.id
        typer.echo(
            f"Auto-parenting under: "
            f"#{active.id} {active.title}"
        )
if resolved_parent is not None:
    parent_item = next(
        (t for t in todos if t.id == resolved_parent),
        None,
    )
    if parent_item is None:
        typer.echo(
            f"Error: parent #{resolved_parent} not found",
            err=True,
        )
        raise typer.Exit(1)

inherited_labels = []
inherited_deadline = deadline
if resolved_parent is not None:
    if not label and parent_item.labels:
        inherited_labels = list(parent_item.labels)
    if deadline is None and parent_item.deadline:
        inherited_deadline = parent_item.deadline

<<resolve wd and env for new todo>>
@

When [[--number]] is given we bypass the list API entirely and
call [[gh_fetch_issue]] or [[gh_fetch_pr]] directly---fetching
100 items just to extract one is wasteful, especially in large
repos where pagination would be needed. The fetch functions do
not include [[number]] or [[createdAt]] in their JSON fields
(those were omitted because the view commands use them for
display, not import), so we inject both manually: [[number]]
comes from the CLI argument, and [[createdAt]] falls back to
[[GH_FALLBACK_CREATED]] so the age heuristic places the item
at the bottom if [[--skip-priority]] is used.

Issues and PRs share the same number sequence in a
repository---GitHub's internal model treats PRs as a
specialisation of issues---so [[#5]] is \emph{either} an issue
or a PR, never both. When [[--type]] is [[all]] and [[--number]]
is given, we cannot determine the type from the number alone. We
default to [[issue]] (by far the common case); the user must
pass [[--type pr]] explicitly to import a pull request.

<<fetch github items>>=
gh_items = []
if number is not None:
    <<fetch single github item>>
else:
    <<fetch all github items>>
@

<<fetch single github item>>=
effective_type = (
    item_type if item_type != "all" else "issue"
)
if effective_type == "pr":
    data = gh_fetch_pr(repo, number)
else:
    data = gh_fetch_issue(repo, number)
data["_type"] = effective_type
data["number"] = number
data["createdAt"] = GH_FALLBACK_CREATED
gh_items.append(data)
@

We fetch issues, PRs, or both depending on the [[--type]] flag:

<<fetch all github items>>=
if item_type in ("all", "issue"):
    for issue in gh_list_issues(repo):
        issue["_type"] = "issue"
        gh_items.append(issue)
if item_type in ("all", "pr"):
    for pr in gh_list_prs(repo):
        pr["_type"] = "pr"
        gh_items.append(pr)
@

We skip items that already exist locally by matching on repo,
type, and number---preventing duplicate imports:

<<filter already imported>>=
existing = set()
for t in todos:
    if t.github:
        key = (
            t.github["repo"],
            t.github.get("type", "issue"),
            t.github["number"],
        )
        existing.add(key)

new_items = []
for gh_item in gh_items:
    key = (
        repo,
        gh_item["_type"],
        str(gh_item["number"]),
    )
    if key not in existing:
        new_items.append(gh_item)
@

The age-based priority heuristic scales creation timestamps
linearly so that the newest item in the batch gets the highest
priority. If the user prefers interactive ranking, we fall back
to binary search.

When importing from multiple repositories, filtering by
repository is the most common need---but requiring users to
remember [[--label owner/repo]] on every import is error-prone.
We therefore always include the repository name as a label.
GitHub's own labels (such as [[bug]] or [[enhancement]]) tend
to be project-specific and would clutter a cross-repository
task list, so they are only included when [[--github-labels]]
is passed. Any additional labels supplied via [[--label]] on
the command line are appended last.

<<create todos from github items>>=
if skip_priority and new_items:
    <<compute age-based priorities>>
else:
    priorities = {}

imported_count = 0
for gh_item in new_items:
    gh_labels = list(inherited_labels)
    if repo not in gh_labels:
        gh_labels.append(repo)
    if github_labels:
        gh_labels.extend(
            lb["name"]
            for lb in gh_item.get("labels", [])
        )
    if label:
        gh_labels.extend(label)

    gh_state = gh_item.get("state", "OPEN")
    status = (
        "done"
        if gh_state in ("CLOSED", "MERGED")
        else "pending"
    )

    if parent_item is not None and parent_item.priority is None:
        priority = None
    elif skip_priority:
        priority = priorities.get(
            gh_item["number"], 0.0
        )
    else:
        candidate = TodoItem(
            id=0,
            title=gh_item["title"],
            labels=gh_labels,
            parent_id=resolved_parent,
            deadline=inherited_deadline,
            estimated=(
                parse_hours(estimate)
                if estimate else None
            ),
        )
        active = get_active_siblings(
            todos, candidate, who=who
        )
        priority = binary_search_priority(
            active, candidate,
            parent=parent_item,
            todos=todos,
        )

    item = TodoItem(
        id=next_id,
        title=gh_item["title"],
        labels=gh_labels,
        priority=priority,
        status=status,
        who=who,
        created=(
            datetime.datetime.now().isoformat()
        ),
        deadline=inherited_deadline,
        estimated=(
            parse_hours(estimate)
            if estimate else None
        ),
        description=description or "",
        parent_id=resolved_parent,
        wd=resolved_wd,
        env=resolved_env,
        command=run_command,
        github={
            "repo": repo,
            "type": gh_item["_type"],
            "number": str(gh_item["number"]),
        },
    )
    todos.append(item)
    next_id += 1
    imported_count += 1
    typer.echo(
        f"  #{item.id} {item.title} "
        f"({gh_item['_type']} "
        f"#{gh_item['number']})"
    )
@

The age heuristic maps creation dates to priorities in the
range~$[0, 1]$, with the oldest item at~0 and the newest at~1.
Users can later reprioritize individual items to interleave
them with existing work.  When we import under a ranked parent,
however, those priorities must stay within the parent's child
range or flat view would scatter them outside their subtree.
In that case we scale the same oldest-to-newest ordering into
the interval returned by [[compute_child_priority_range]].

An unranked parent has no numeric child interval yet.  In that
case the imported children stay unranked too, regardless of
whether the user asked for the age heuristic or the interactive
path.

Items missing a [[createdAt]] field (malformed API responses) get a
far-past fallback so they sort to the bottom of the batch:

<<constants>>=
GH_FALLBACK_CREATED = "2020-01-01T00:00:00Z"
@

<<compute age-based priorities>>=
timestamps = []
for gh_item in new_items:
    created = gh_item.get(
        "createdAt", GH_FALLBACK_CREATED
    )
    dt = datetime.datetime.fromisoformat(
        created.replace("Z", "+00:00")
    )
    timestamps.append((dt, gh_item["number"]))

timestamps.sort()
n = len(timestamps)
if resolved_parent is not None and parent_item is not None:
    if parent_item.priority is None:
        priorities = {
            num: None
            for _, num in timestamps
        }
    else:
        high, low = compute_child_priority_range(
            todos, parent_item
        )
        values = distribute_priorities_in_range(
            n, high, low
        )
        priorities = {}
        for i, (dt, num) in enumerate(reversed(timestamps)):
            priorities[num] = values[i]
elif n == 1:
    priorities = {timestamps[0][1]: 0.0}
else:
    priorities = {}
    for i, (dt, num) in enumerate(timestamps):
        priorities[num] = float(i) / (n - 1)
